Analyzing the Training Set of Japanese Active Population

After splitting the Japanese Active Population data set into the first 80% training and the latter 20% for testing, I plot the training set with its ACF and PACF.
The training set exibits seasonality and a trend that grows first but latter falls. In a given year, the population tends to peak between April to July, dips a little around Augest. It rises again between September and October. It gradually falls from November to Feburary, but start rising in March.

The training set series doesnt pass the ADF stationarity test or the Box-Ljung Test of independence up to 24 lags. We might need to take its differences.


The training sets ACF decays very slowly. But its PACF drops around the 95% confidence interval after lag 2, suggesting an AR2 process. Since the cut isnt clear, I will try out various ARMA models.


Models

Model using 5th Polynomial Trend with Season

AIC= 365.3587 SIC= 439.405
This models training set residuals pass the ADF stationarity test at 5% critical value, but not the Box-Ljung test of independence up to 24 lags.
Its residuals from the training set have a mean around 0. But the ACF and the PACF suggests at least some AR effcts, probably an order of 2.

The test set residuals pass the ADF stationarity test at 5% critical value, but not the Box-Ljung test of independence up to 24 lags.


Model using ARIMA(0,1,2)(1,1,1)[12]

The auto.arima() function run through more than 20 models to find the one with the lowest AIC. And we get ARIMA(0,1,2)(1,1,1)[12], AIC= -205.5893 SIC= -185.1668.

 ARIMA(0,1,2)(1,1,1)[12]                    : -205.5893

 Best model: ARIMA(0,1,2)(1,1,1)[12]

This models training set residuals pass both the ADF stationarity test at the 5% critical value and the Box-Ljung test of independence up to 24 lags. The residual series resemble a white noise process. Neither the ACF or the PACF go beyond the 95% confidence interval, suggesting no ARMA effects.

The test set residuals pass the ADF stationarity test at 5% critical value, but not the Box-Ljung test of independence up to 24 lags.

Comparing Forecasting Performances

The linear model overestiamtes, but the ARIMA model underestimates.
Comparing the test set error measures, the ARIMA model outperforms the linear model, except for a higher Autocorrelation of errors at lag 1 (ACF1).
